@Node Introduction " Maj-Jongg Full Documentation"

            @{b}  I n t r o d u c t i o n   a n d   H i s t o r y @{ub}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

	  Maj-Jongg is an oriental table-game which has been enjoyed
	worldwide for many years.
	
	When the game first became popular in America during the 1920's
	its already complicated rules evolved and became more
	conveluted. This produced more variations of the rules than
	could be counted.

          Our puzzle game, is not based on the original Mah-Jongg, but
	retains the brightly coloured tiles which made the original so
	attractive.

	  A single player will try to remove all the tiles from a stack,
	known as 'The Dragon'. He will select a tile and look for its
	'Twin' elsewhere in the stack. To remove the tiles they must also
	be 'free'. A free tile will have no tile directly on top of it,
	and a gap to its left and/or right, allowing it to slide sideways.

	  A tile's 'Twin' means that the two tiles you select must match
	exactly. Only in the case of Flowers and Seasons can you select
	non-matching tiles, for instance you can remove an Orchid and Plum
	or Summer and Winter quite legally. Several tiles are very similar
	but do not match exactly; the Character tiles have a different
	number and symbol on each but appear closely matched, so be careful.
	See the section on the tiles and their suits to understand better
	the tiles and relationships. @{">>" link Tiles}

	  You can check whether a tile is free by selecting the
	'show free tiles' gadget at the bottom of the screen. This is a
	feature provided for a beginner. In a very short time you will be
	able to decide whether a tile is free or not at a glance.

	  At the start of play there are 144 tiles in the Dragon, these are
	brightly coloured, and stacked in a certain way. If you have trouble
	in deciding which tiles are on which level you can use the
	'show layers' gadget. This illuminates every other row in pale pink,
	making it easier to view the stack's layers. This is again, a
	helpful feature for the beginner; you will quickly learn to scan the
	stack without any confusion.

	  The gadgets also allow you to replace the last move you made, and
	even ask the computer for a suggestion for your next move. This is
	however, a suggestion for a possible move, you must decide which
	move will be the wisest. It is not always possible to complete
	the game, and it is never easy. See the section on Solitaire
	strategy for more help on making good moves. @{">>" link Playing }


@EndNode

