@Node Playing " Maj-Jongg Full Documentation"

                      @{b}  S o l i t a i r e   G a m e @{ub}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

	GAMEPLAY
	--------

	  Start a new game from the Main Menu. You are presented with a
	new, complete Dragon. In single-player mode you have unlimited time
	to complete your move, so take your time and search around for two
	matching tiles. To remove a pair, click once on the first tile; if
	it is 'free' and therefore a valid selection it will highlight, then
	click once on the second tile. The tiles will now be removed, or you
	will be told that the second tile is not free, or that the tiles
	do not match.

	  If you find a better move, you can go back one step - replacing
	the last pair you removed, by clicking the 'replace last move' icon
	at the bottom of the screen.

	  Now select a new pair and keep removing until the Dragon is
	completed. It is not always possible to complete the Dragon. Due
	to either the choices you made, or an unfortunate tile placing,
	But as you learn, you will find yourself getting closer to
	completion each time.



	STRATEGY
	--------
                      S e c r e t s   o f   M a j - J o n g g

	  There is a feature in this game called 'peek'. This allows you,
	at any time to forfeit the game and remove single tiles at will
	by clicking once on each. This feature allows you to find out
	the location of a hidden tile that you may have been searching for.
	It is simply to satisfy your curiosity; the game cannot be continued.

  	  To enter 'peek' mode. Click once on the 'exit game' icon with the
	right mouse button. You will notice the 'help option' icons
	disappear; as these are not needed to 'peek'.


	These are some invaluable tips, toward better playing.


	1. Use the 'help icons' whilst you learn the game.

		Using 'show layers' and 'show free tiles' will help you
		to find better moves in the early stages, and enhance
		your chances greatly.


	2. Check for 'Triples'

		Sometimes you will find three of four matching tiles
		available at once. You must decide at these points
		which two to take. The general rule is to take the ones
		which will free the most tiles thereafter.


	3. Think ahead.

		Locate the tiles which need to be removed as soon as
		possible. The far left and right tiles, also the very
		top tile should be your immediate targets. If the matching
		tiles to these are visible, try to free them up by working
		along rows.


	4. Choose wisely.

		Never take easy moves immediately. Keep looking for 'triples'
		or better moves, and come back later.


	5. Work on long rows.

		Concentrate on breaking long rows of tiles, before high
		stacks. Long rows have only two free tiles (one at each
		end) and are harder to break. High stacks have short rows
		with many more free tiles and are easier to break, once
		you start to get stuck.


	6. Save your game.

		You may find it useful to save a game at the start of play.
		Then again when you find yourself faced with a choice of
		directions. If you forsee a long string of tiles which can
		be removed sequencially, it may be wise to save first and
		make sure that it doesn't dry up and leave you stuck.

		You can only have one savegame, or 'game in progress' on disk
		but it is saved and restored very quickly.


	7. Don't overuse the 'suggest move' icon.

		The 'suggest move' option does not give you a calculated
		decision on the best move to make. It provides you with
		a quick pair, when you are finding it hard to locate any
		moves at all.

		Overuse of this function stops you from making good
		decisions, - it does not allow for triples or long strings
		of pairs.

@EndNode

@Node Challenges " Maj-Jongg Full Documentation"

                    @{b} C h a l l e n g e   M a t c h e s@{ub}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

	A challenge match follows the same rules as solitaire play.
	
	  Two players compete to finish the Dragon. If you are not able to
	complete the Dragon, the player who has removed the most tiles from
	it wins. If both players have removed the same number of tiles at
	the end if play, the match is drawn.

	  Each player takes a turn, he has the count of sixty to find and
	complete a suitable move. 

	  Decide who will be player 1 and player 2. At the bottom of the
	screen you will see either 'PL1' or 'PL2', this indicates whose
	turn it is at that time. The cursor will also have '1' or '2'
	next to it.

	  Next to the player legend is a countdown. Once this reaches zero,
	four gongs will chime and it is the next player's turn.

	  None of the 'help options' such as 'replace last tile' or 
	'suggest move' are available during a challenge.



	S T R A T E G Y
	---------------

	When playing a challenge, the object is no longer to complete the
	Dragon by selecting reasoned, strategic tiles to remove. You must
	simply remove more than your opponent. To do this start looking
	for pairs - any pair - immediately as the game starts.

	  When you find a move, make it quickly. Whilst your opponent
	seeks a move, continue looking yourself, for not only one move -
	find as many pairs as you can whilst you wait. This gives you an
	advantage in time as each move is made very quickly, giving
	yourself the maximum amount of time to find tiles, and your
	opponent the least.

	
@EndNode

@Node Control " Maj-Jongg Full Documentation"

                     @{b}  C o n t r o l   G a d g e t s @{ub}
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

	During play there are several gadgets at the bottom of the screen.

	Moving the cursor over these gadgets will display a explanation of
	these. Clicking once with the left mouse-button will select it.

	Here is a full explanation of these gadgets.

	1. Suggest move.
		
		The computer will find two matching, free tiles on the
		Dragon and highlight them in pale pink. It is simply a
		suggestion of a possible move. See 'solitaire - strategy'
		section 7. for notes on its use. @{">>" link Playing}


	2. Replace Last Move.

		Simply replaces the last two tiles removed from the Dragon.
		You may wish to go back on your last move, or select a
		different triple.


	3. Show Free Tiles.

		Selecting this option will highlight all 'free' tiles in
		pale pink. These will stay highlighted, and subsequent
		tiles becoming free will highlight untill the option is
		clicked again to turn the function off.


	4. Show Layers.

		Designed for the beginner, this highlights layer 2, 4 and
		6 in pale pink, helping to distinguish between different
		heights of stacked tiles in case of confusion. The option
		remains untill it is selected again, turning if off.
		You can show only free tiles, or layers - never both.


	5. Music Toggle.

		Unsurprisingly turns the music either on or off. You will
		notice that during a challenge match the music will fade
		out just before the chimes which indicate a player's
		time-out, and fades back in afterwards.


	6. Save Current Game.

		This will save your game to date. Keep the disk
		write-enabled to allow this function. You can now pick
		up the game again at any time.

	
	7. Load Game In Progress.

		You can continue a saved game by selecting this option.
		Alternatively choose 'continue game' from the main option
		screen. You will notice that a save game also keeps your
		last move, which can be replaced if desired.


	8. Exit Game / Challenge.

		Quits the current game and returns to the main options
		screen. Using right mouse-button instead of left, enters
		'peek' mode. See 'solitaire - strategy' for notes on the
		use of the peek mode. @{">>" link Playing}

@Endnode

